Present law (R.S. 36:508(F)) requires the chief engineer approve all plans, specifications,
and estimates for the construction of all facilities and projects for which his office is
responsible. Further requires that he have other duties that may be assigned to him by the
secretary or the assistant secretary, by the provisions of present law, or by the laws of this
state. Additionally requires he report his proceedings of his office annually to the secretary
of the DOTD and any other times as designated by secretary, and he must make any
additional reports as are required by the secretary.
Proposed law clarifies present law by changing from his office to the office applicable to the
chief engineer's approval of all plans, specifications, and estimates for construction of all
facilities and projects. Further changes from the proceedings of his office to his proceedings
in the annual report to the secretary.
Present law (R.S. 36:508.2(A)) creates the office of operations within the DOTD, which
administers all matters related to the operations of the DOTD district offices, and other
matters directed by the secretary.
Proposed law authorizes the chief operating officer to direct the operations within the office
of operations.
Present law (R.S. 36:508.2(B)) requires the office of operations be under the immediate
supervision of the assistant secretary, who is appointed by the governor and serves at the
pleasure of the secretary.
Proposed law specifies that the chief operating officer directly supervise the assistant
secretary within the office of operations.
Present law (R.S. 36:508.2(C)) requires the assistant secretary have authority, subject to the
approval of the secretary and in accordance with applicable rules and regulations of the civil
service commission, to employ, appoint, transfer, assign, and promote personnel as is
necessary for the efficient administration of the office of operations.
Proposed law includes the chief operating officer as one to approve the assistant secretary's
authority to employ, appoint, transfer, assign, and promote personnel as is necessary for the
efficient administration of the office of operations.
Present law (R.S. 36:508.2(E)) requires the secretary assign the assistant secretary functions
and duties within the office of operations. Further requires the assistant secretary report the
proceedings of his office annually to the secretary of the DOTD and authorizes the secretary
to designate, and make any additional reports as are required by the secretary.
Proposed law authorizes the chief operating officer to assign duties to the assistant secretary
within the office of operations. Further changes the requirement from reporting to the
secretary to reporting to the chief operating officer.
Present law (R.S. 36:508.2(F)) provides for the specific authorization of the secretary to
perform any of the duties of the assistant secretary when the assistant secretary is absent or
incapacitated or when the secretary deems it would be in the best interest of the DOTD.
Further authorizes the assistant secretary with approval of the secretary to designate a senior
staff member in the office of operations to perform any duties required by the assistant
secretary.
Proposed law adds the chief operating officer as one authorized to perform any duties of the
assistant secretary in the event he is absent, incapacitated, or if the chief operating officer
deems it is in the best interest of the DOTD. Additionally replaces the secretary with the
chief operating officer as the one to approve the assistant secretary's designation of a senior
staff member in the office of operations to perform any duties required by the assistant
secretary.
